Problem Statement:¶

The dataset provided is a synthetic dataset generated using a CTGAN based on a original dataset. The original dataset was used to predict the amount of an insurance claim. The features provided in this synthetic dataset have some similarities and properties relating to real-world features.

Objective for this dataset is also to predict an amount of insurance claim based on the features provided.

Observation:¶
  1. Training set has 300000 data points with 26 features, test having 200000 data points with 25 features. The extra feature for training set being the target/insurance claim.
  2. Both the training and test dataset have 10 categorical features, 14 continous/numerical features and id.
  3. Zero missing values present for both the datasets.
  4. Feature distribution for both the sets is fairly similar on first look, the only difference being the presence of a extra unique value in the training set for 'cat6'.

In [40]:
"""The scikit-learn algorithm for MI treats discrete features differently from continuous features. Consequently, you need to tell it which are which. As a rule of thumb, anything that must have a float dtype is not discrete. Categoricals (object or categorial dtype) can be treated as discrete by giving them a label encoding. """
Out[40]:
'The scikit-learn algorithm for MI treats discrete features differently from continuous features. Consequently, you need to tell it which are which. As a rule of thumb, anything that must have a float dtype is not discrete. Categoricals (object or categorial dtype) can be treated as discrete by giving them a label encoding. '
In [41]:
#Label Encoding for categoricals

le = LabelEncoder()
for feature in cat:
    X[feature] = le.fit_transform(X[feature])
In [42]:
discrete_features = X.dtypes == int #Double check this before implimentation
In [43]:
def mi_scores(X,y,discrete_features):
    mi = mutual_info_regression(X,y,discrete_features=discrete_features)
    mi = pd.Series(mi, name="MI Scores",index = X.columns)
    mi = mi.sort_values(ascending=False)
    return mi
In [44]:
mi = mi_scores(X,y,discrete_features)

Model implimentation¶

Process:¶

  1. Splitting the training data set using train_test_split for testing
  2. First we will encode the categorical features using One Hot Encoder as these features are nominal in nature.
  3. In the second step we will scale the continous features to a normal distribution using Standard Scaler.
  4. A function model is defined which will take values for valrious parameters of the model, this function will help in initialising a model with the said values and comparing accuracies so the right parameters can be determined.
  5. Once the right parameters have been determined we can use these paramters to train the complete training set.
  6. The test data set is also transfommed through steps 1 and 2 and then we can get predictions which can be submitted on kaggle.

In [103]:
#As the variables are nominal we will encode them with OHE
OH = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore',sparse = False)
OH_col_train = pd.DataFrame(OH.fit_transform(X_train[cat]))
OH_col_valid = pd.DataFrame(OH.transform(X_valid[cat]))

OH_col_train.index = X_train.index
OH_col_valid.index = X_valid.index

num_X_train = X_train.drop(cat,axis=1)
num_X_valid = X_valid.drop(cat,axis=1)

OH_X_train = pd.concat([num_X_train,OH_col_train],axis =1)
OH_X_valid = pd.concat([num_X_valid,OH_col_valid],axis=1)

def model(n,tree,rate):
    XGB=XGBRegressor(n_estimators=n,max_depth=tree,learning_rate=rate,n_jobs=4,random_state=0)
    XGB.fit(OH_X_train,y_train)
    predictions = XGB.predict(OH_X_valid)
    print(f"mean absolute error: {mean_absolute_error(y_valid,predictions)} for n_estimators:{n},tree_depth:{tree} and learning rate:{rate} ")
